SIMPLE: foil
RECORDS: 4

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Foil
<hw>Foil</hw> <pr>(foil)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Foiled</conjf> <pr>(foild)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Foiling</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[F. <ets>fouler</ets> to
tread or trample under one's feet, to press, oppress. See <er>Full</er>,
<pos>v. t.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To tread under foot; to
trample.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q> King Richard . . . caused the ensigns of Leopold to be pulled
down and <qex>foiled</qex> under foot.</q>
<rj><qau>Knoless.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q> Whom he did all to pieces breake and <qex>foyle</qex>,⟦br⟧
In filthy durt, and left so in the loathely soyle.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To render (an effort or attempt) vain or nugatory;
to baffle; to outwit; to balk; to frustrate; to defeat.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q> And by <?/ mortal man at length am <qex>foiled</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q> Her long locks that <qex>foil</qex> the painter's power.</q>
<rj><qau>Byron.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To blunt; to dull; to spoil; <as>as, to
<ex>foil</ex> the scent in chase</as>.</def>
<rj><au>Addison.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Foil</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Foil
<hw>Foil</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <ety>[See 6th <er>File</er>.]</ety>
<def>To defile; to soil.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Foil</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Foil
<hw>Foil</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Failure of success when on
the point of attainment; defeat; frustration; miscarriage.</def>
<rj><au>Milton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q> Nor e'er was fate so near a <qex>foil</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A blunt weapon used in fencing, resembling a
smallsword in the main, but usually lighter and having a button at the
point.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q> Blunt as the fencer's <qex>foils</qex>, which hit, but hurt
not.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q> Isocrates contended with a <qex>foil</qex> against Demosthenes
with a word.</q> <rj><qau>Mitford.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>The track or trail of an animal.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To run a foil</b></col>,<cd>to lead astray; to puzzle; --
alluding to the habits of some animals of running back over the same
track to mislead their pursuers.</cd> <rj><au>Brewer.</au></rj></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Foil</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Foil
<hw>Foil</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>foil</ets> leaf, OF.
<ets>foil</ets>, <ets>fuil</ets>, <ets>fueil</ets>, <ets>foille</ets>,
<ets>fueille</ets>, F. <ets>feuille</ets>, fr. L. <ets>folium</ets>, pl.
<ets>folia</ets>; akin to Gr. <?/ , and perh. to E. <ets>blade</ets>.
Cf. <er>Foliage</er>, <er>Folio</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A leaf or
very thin sheet of metal; <as>as, brass <ex>foil</ex>; tin
<ex>foil</ex>; gold <ex>foil</ex>.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Jewelry)</fld> <def>A thin leaf of sheet copper
silvered and burnished, and afterwards coated with transparent colors
mixed with isinglass; -- employed by jewelers to give color or
brilliancy to pastes and inferior stones.</def>
<rj><au>Ure.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Anything that serves by contrast of color or quality
to adorn or set off another thing to advantage.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>As she a black silk cap on him began⟦br⟧
To set, for <qex>foil</qex> of his milk-white to serve.</q> <rj><qau>Sir
P. Sidney.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Hector has a <qex>foil</qex> to set him off.</q>
<rj><qau>Broome.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>A thin coat of tin, with quicksilver, laid on the
back of a looking-glass, to cause reflection.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <fld>(Arch.)</fld> <def>The space between the cusps in
Gothic architecture; a rounded or leaflike ornament, in windows, niches,
etc. A group of foils is called trefoil, quatrefoil, quinquefoil, etc.,
according to the number of arcs of which it is composed.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Foil stone</b></col>, <cd>an imitation of a jewel or
precious stone.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Foilable</ent>⟦br⟧
